Let $p$ be an odd prime and $L_n$ be the $n$th Lucas number. Can anyone prove this? $$ rac{L_1}{1}+ rac{L_3}{3}+ rac{L_5}{5}+\cdots+ rac{L_{p-2}}{p-2}
eq0\pmod{p}$$ Please help me! I am thinking about the period of Fibonacci sequence. The purpose is to prove that (the period mod $p$) $
eq$ (the period mod $p^2$). It is known that the period mod $p$ divides $p-1$ or $2p+2\ (p
eq5)$. So, I tried to prove $F^{p^2-1}
eq I\ \pmod{p^2}$, where $F$ is the Fibonacci matrix, then I got this inequality. If $p
eq5$, this question is equivalent to prove that $$ rac{\phi}{1}+ rac{\phi^2}{2}+ rac{\phi^3}{3}+\cdots+ rac{\phi^{p-1}}{p-1}
eq0\pmod{p}.$$ Here, $\phi$ is a root of $x^2-x-1$. See this page . I have showed that $$ rac{\phi}{1}+ rac{\phi^2}{2}+ rac{\phi^3}{3}+\cdots+ rac{\phi^{p-1}}{p-1}\equiv\sum_{k=1}^{ rac{p-1}{2}}  rac{{(-1)}^k}{2k} {{2k}\choose{k}}\pmod{p}.$$

